Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original idea presents a strong foundation by modeling collaborative error recovery as a joint inference problem, it still treats grounding and repair as internal system processes without fully accounting for the *user’s agency* in co-constructing understanding. Drawing inspiration from Paper 2’s emphasis on user adaptation and Paper 3’s focus on complementary information control, I propose shifting from a system-centric joint inference model to a *bidirectional alignment framework* that explicitly models not only how the system interprets user signals but also how users update their mental model of the system. The key insight is that effective error recovery is not just about the system detecting inconsistencies—it's about both agents dynamically aligning their expectations. My new idea introduces a dual-latent alignment architecture where both system-to-user and user-to-system belief tracking are modeled simultaneously, using contrastive learning over dialogue trajectories to capture misalignment patterns. Furthermore, instead of relying solely on predefined repair strategies, the model learns to generate *adaptive rationalizations*—explanations of its own reasoning that help the user realign—inspired by Paper 3’s introspective rationalization. This transforms error recovery from a corrective action into a transparent, cooperative sense-making process. Unlike prior work, this approach does not assume the user passively provides feedback; rather, it anticipates how users will react based on observed adaptability (e.g., whether they tend to self-correct, rephrase, or take over tasks). By integrating simulated user adaptation behaviors during training—using behavioral priors derived from human data—the model becomes robust to diverse interaction styles. This significantly advances beyond modular pipelines or even joint inference models by embedding reciprocity into the core architecture.

